<doc id="373810" wikidata="Q129638" url="?curid=373810" title="Grassmannian">
<text>In mathematics, the Grassmannian formula_1 (named in honour of Hermann Grassmann) is a differentiable manifold that parameterizes the set of all formula_2-dimensional linear subspaces of an formula_3-dimensional vector space formula_4 over a field formula_5 that has a differentiable structure. 
For example, the Grassmannian formula_6 is the space of lines through the origin in formula_4, so it is the same as the projective space formula_8 of one dimension lower than formula_4.
When formula_4 is a real or complex vector space, Grassmannians are compact smooth manifolds, of dimension formula_11. In general they have the structure of a nonsingular projective algebraic variety.

The earliest work on a non-trivial Grassmannian is due to Julius Plücker, who studied the set of projective lines in real projective 3-space, which is equivalent to formula_12, parameterizing them by what are now called Plücker coordinates. (See below.) Hermann Grassmann later introduced the concept in general.

Notations for Grassmannians vary between authors; they include formula_1, formula_14,formula_15, formula_16 to denote the Grassmannian of formula_2-dimensional subspaces of an formula_3-dimensional vector space formula_4.

==Motivation==
By giving a collection of subspaces of a vector space a topological structure, it is possible to talk about a continuous choice of subspaces or open and closed collections of subspaces. Giving them the further structure of a differentiable manifold, one can talk about smooth choices of subspace.

A natural example comes from tangent bundles of smooth manifolds embedded in a Euclidean space. Suppose we have a manifold formula_20 of dimension formula_2 embedded in formula_22. At each point formula_23, the tangent space to formula_20 can be considered as a subspace of the tangent space of formula_22, which is also just formula_22. The map assigning to formula_27 its tangent space defines a map from to formula_28. (In order to do this, we have to translate the tangent space at each formula_29 so that it passes through the origin rather than formula_30, and hence defines a formula_2-dimensional vector subspace. This idea is very similar to the Gauss map for surfaces in a 3-dimensional space.)

This can with some effort be extended to all vector bundles over a manifold formula_20, so that every vector bundle generates a continuous map from formula_20 to a suitably generalised Grassmannian—although various embedding theorems must be proved to show this. We then find that the properties of our vector bundles are related to the properties of the corresponding maps. In particular we find that vector bundles inducing homotopic maps to the Grassmannian are isomorphic. Here the definition of homotopy relies on a notion of continuity, and hence a topology.

==Low dimensions==
For , the Grassmannian is the space of lines through the origin in -space, so it is the same as the projective space formula_34of dimensions.

For , the Grassmannian is the space of all 2-dimensional planes containing the origin. In Euclidean 3-space, a plane containing the origin is completely characterized by the one and only line through the origin that is perpendicular to that plane (and vice versa); hence the spaces , , and (the projective plane) may all be identified with each other.

The simplest Grassmannian that is not a projective space is .

== The Grassmannian as a differentiable manifold ==

To endow formula_1 with the structure of a differentiable manifold, choose a basis for formula_4. This is equivalent to identifying formula_4 with formula_38, with the standard basis denoted formula_39, viewed as column vectors. Then for any formula_2-dimensional subspace formula_41, viewed as an element of formula_1, we may choose a basis consisting of formula_2 linearly independent column vectors formula_44. The homogeneous coordinates of the element formula_45 consist of the elements of the formula_46 maximal rank rectangular matrix formula_47 whose formula_48-th column vector is formula_49, formula_50. Since the choice of basis is arbitrary, two such maximal rank rectangular matrices formula_47 and formula_52 represent the same element formula_53 if and only if 
