== The Grassmannian as a set of orthogonal projections ==
An alternative way to define a real or complex Grassmannian as a manifold is to view it as a set of orthogonal projection operators ( problem 5-C). For this, choose a positive definite real or Hermitian inner product formula_125 on formula_4, depending on whether formula_4 is real or complex. A formula_2-dimensional subspace formula_72 determines a unique orthogonal projection operator formula_130 whose image is formula_41 by splitting formula_4 into the orthogonal direct sum
::formula_133
of formula_72 and its orthogonal complement formula_135 and defining
::formula_136 
Conversely, every projection operator formula_137 of rank formula_2 defines a subspace formula_139 as its image. Since the rank of an orthogonal projection operator equals its trace, we can identify the Grassmann manifold formula_140 with the set of rank formula_2 orthogonal projection operators formula_137: 
::formula_143

In particular, taking formula_144 or formula_145 this gives completely explicit equations for embedding the Grassmannians formula_146, formula_147 in the space of real or complex formula_148 matrices formula_149, formula_150, respectively.

Since this defines the Grassmannian as a closed subset of the sphere formula_151 this is one way to see that the Grassmannian is a compact Hausdorff space. This construction also turns the Grassmannian formula_152 into a metric space with metric
::formula_153
for any pair formula_154 of formula_2-dimensional subspaces, where denotes the operator norm. The exact inner product used does not matter, because a different inner product will give an equivalent norm on formula_4, and hence an equivalent metric.

For the case of real or complex Grassmannians, the following is an equivalent way to express the above construction in terms of matrices.

